 cemetery tourism all come into play as Kammen delves deeply into this little-known—yet surprisingly persistent—aspect of American history. Simultaneously insightful and interesting, masterly and macabre, Digging Up the Dead reminds us that the stories of American history don’t always end when the key players pass on. Rather, the battle—over reputations, interpretations, and, last but far from least, possession of the remains themselves—is often just beginning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBurialxHistoryxUnited States. 0aBurialzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aExhumationxHistoryxUnited States. 0aExhumationxPolitical aspectsxUnited States. 0aExhumationxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aExhumationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aFuneral rites and ceremoniesxHistoryxUnited States. 0aFuneral rites and ceremonieszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aburial, reburial, monument, history, fame, celebrity, memorial, abraham lincoln, jefferson davis, daniel boone, frank lloyd wright, john paul jones, sitting bull, graveyard, resting place, cemetery tourism, mistaken identity, skull fondling, graverobbing, reputation, exhumation, funeral, revolution, heroism, patriotism, founding fathers, sectionalism, nationalism, religion, race, spirituality, nonfiction, politics.1 aKammen, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226423326423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226423326/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles